<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 93 / Banks warn BT to cut cost of card fraud checks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BANKS and credit card companies have warned BT that they may use US
telecommunications companies or Mercury, a competitor, to carry out
electronic fraud checks on card purchases unless BT cuts charges
substantially.
The credit and debit card companies have also warned that, if they do not
win lower prices for 'on-line' verification, they may install technology in
shops to allow them to check for fraud without using telecommunications
links.
The warnings have been given in joint talks between the banks, credit card
companies and BT over the price for the rapidly growing number of on-line
fraud checks, which the banks believe may reach 1bn a year by 1996.
BT emphasised yesterday that it intended to offer price reductions and
wanted a deal that would allow the market to expand.
Mr Peter Macleod, who is leading negotiations for BT, said the company was
encouraging a deal based on lower prices and higher volume. He said: 'We see
it as an attractive market.'
Mr Macleod said BT realised that the authentication business could be
offered to competitors if it did not reach a deal.
Credit and debit card companies and the banks that process card transactions
for retailers are worried at the growth of fraud, which cost the industry
Pounds 165.6m in 1991, and an estimated 10 per cent more last year.
However, fewer than one in five of last year's 1.2bn card transactions were
checked for fraud via telecommunications lines, against an 85 per cent check
rate in the US. Card companies blame that on the high cost of UK
telecommunications.
Mr Mervyn Gibson, who is leading talks for the banks and card companies,
said there was 'no indication of any impasse' with BT. He said they were
offering BT potential business volumes that deserved a 'substantial
reduction'.
Mr Gibson said the banks and card companies had 'made BT aware' of the
options. These included negotiating fresh contracts with US
telecommunications companies, and possibly offering some business to
Mercury, BT's UK rival.
BT agreed a deal with Barclays and National Westminster Bank last year that
halved the cost of fraud checks via BT's network. Barclays estimates that
each on-line check now costs a total of 4.5p in telecommunications charges.
Mr Richard Reay-Smith, chief executive of Barclays central retail services,
said UK telecommunications costs were 'still very high' compared with the
US, and unless they were cut, banks might opt for forms of fraud check that
avoided them.
He said card processing companies in France had opted for 'off-line' checks
such as asking customers using cards to key in a personal identification
number at the point of sale.
Paris tries to avert telecoms split, Page 3
</TEXT>
