<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 93 / EBRD under fire for lack of impact on eastern Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE EUROPEAN Bank for Reconstruction and Development's investments have made
an inadequate impact on eastern Europe's economies, according to a
confidential report commissioned by Mr Jacques Attali, the bank's president.
The report - by Mr Martin Paijmans and Mr Stanley Katz, consultants who have
worked for the EBRD - says the 'bank's impact comes up short as compared to
the use of its resources'.
In the two years since the bank was created, private-sector financing 'has
been concentrated in fewer than a half-dozen recipient countries (Czech
Republic, Hungary, Poland, Russia)'.
It accuses the EBRD of failing to make a 'coherent . . . contribution to the
(east European) economic transition process'. It adds that when the bank has
funded public-sector projects only a few countries have benefited and
investments have been confined to a few sectors: notably communications,
construction and energy. Of the 25 countries the EBRD can assist, 'some nine
or 10 . . . have received little or no financial assistance'.
In his preface to the report, given to the bank's 23 directors, Mr Attali
says it is 'one element' in his decision to propose a radical reorganisation
of the bank's management. The board has also received a report by Mr Attali
recommending the creation of three senior management positions, all
reporting to him.
He urges, as do Mr Katz and Mr Paijmans, that the bank's development banking
and merchant banking operations should be merged and divided into three
'operations departments', each covering a group of countries.
At the moment, merchant banking provides private-sector investments, while
development banking concentrates on financing infrastructure projects.
However, Mr Katz and Mr Paijmans say there is increasing duplication of
staffing and organisations in the two departments, which confuses potential
clients.
They say the bank's basic flaw is that its investments have been based on
the merits of individual projects, rather than the needs of a particular
economy, curbing the bank's influence on the development of the private
sectors in eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union.
Attali proposes shake-up, Page 2
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
