<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Row over cuts in military reserve
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FRESH controversy over cuts in Britain's military strength was stirred up
yesterday after the government announced a reduction of more than 4,000 in
the country's volunteer reserve forces.
Measures announced in the Commons by Mr Malcolm Rifkind, defence secretary,
involve cutting naval reserves by more than half, with a smaller reduction
in RAF part-time forces.
The number of volunteer reserve organisations will be reduced to five with
the scrapping of the 2,700-strong Royal Naval Auxiliary Service.
In addition, the Royal Naval Reserve, already cut from 5,900 to 4,700 under
the Options for Change programme, is to lose a further 1,200 posts. Its
squadron of River Class minesweepers, which Mr Rifkind said had been
overtaken by advances in mine technology, will be withdrawn.
The defence secretary said RNR personnel would be able to serve on more
modern minehunters and announced plans to allow more reservists to join
Royal Navy ships.
The naval cuts will affect almost 300 civilian jobs. Mr Rifkind said not all
would be found alternative work.
The RAF's 1,800-strong volunteer bodies - the Royal Auxiliary Air Force and
the smaller RAF Volunteer Reserve - are to lose about 180 posts.
Mr Rifkind - who also raised the possibility of Territorial Army soldiers
volunteering to join regular army deployments - came under fire from his own
backbenchers.
Mr Julian Brazier, Tory MP for Canterbury, said territorial soldiers would
be put in 'an impossible position' with their employers if they were asked
to volunteer for assignments rather than being called out.
Mr David Clark, shadow defence secretary, asked how much money the proposals
would save. He added: 'At the back of our mind, many of us feel that this is
not a strategic decision based on defence requirements' but was rather based
on the Treasury's decision to screw money out of the Ministry of Defence.
</TEXT>
