<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Clarke stresses strategy to boost
investment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MEASURES to stimulate investment are likely to feature in the November
Budget, Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, indicated in the Commons as Tory
MPs hailed the good set of economic figures announced yesterday.
Tory backbenchers were heartened by a confident performance by the
chancellor, who told Labour critics that they were facing a
'business-friendly' government which would take specific measures to sustain
British industry and commerce.
Mr John Major, the prime minister, provided another boost for Tory morale by
highlighting the significance of the earlier announcement that the jobless
total had fallen for the fourth successive month.
To government cheers, he said it was 'good news for the unemployed, good
news for the economy and good news for Britain'.
Mr Major's robust performance heartened Conservative MPs after a traumatic
few weeks for the government. But most recognised that difficult months lay
ahead, particularly as ministers thrash out public spending decisions.
Mr Clarke, in his first appearance dealing with Treasury questions, was
taunted by Mr Gordon Brown, shadow chancellor, over his reliance on words
rather than action since taking over from Mr Norman Lamont a fortnight ago.
The chancellor said he was working closely with Mr Michael Heseltine, trade
and industry secretary, and Mr David Hunt, employment secretary, and
envisaged that his next 'major contribution' would be in the November
Budget.
In response to challenges from the Labour benches, Mr Clarke said business
investment was low because the economy was just emerging from recession and
in the early stages of recovery.
But he recalled the success achieved in manufacturing and business
investment in the three years to 1989 and stressed 'obviously I will be
considering measures which will sustain that good record once recovery gets
under way'.
Acknowledging that there was also 'a balance of payments problem', Mr Clarke
welcomed the improving export performance, particularly in non-European
Community markets where demand had not been depressed to the same extent.
The government, he said, would do everything possible, through the Treasury
and the Department of Trade and Industry, to support manufacturers in their
efforts to export.
Mr Clarke hoped forecasters would take encouragement from the growth in
gross domestic product, the growth in manufacturing output, and the
announcement that unemployment figures had fallen for the fourth successive
month.
Mr David Willetts (C Havant) said it would be a remarkable achievement if
Britain could secure an economic growth rate higher than the rate of
inflation.
Agreeing, Mr Clarke emphasised: 'It is important firstly to make sure that
does happen in so far as it is within the government's power to do so, and
to make sure that this time we sustain it'.
Mr Alan Beith, Treasury spokesman for the Liberal Democrats, reminded the
chancellor of Mr Lamont's condemnation of interest rate cuts made to offset
some unfavourable political event.
Mr Clarke said such decisions should be taken on the best objective advice
and for good economic reasons, and he promised he would persevere with this
approach.
</TEXT>
