<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Property tenders to be worth Pounds
1.25bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT yesterday announced plans to put Pounds 1.25bn of property
management work out to tender from 1996, through the extension of compulsory
competitive tendering to the management of 4m council houses and flats in
England, John Willman writes.
The services to be put out to tender include rent collection, allocating
properties and arranging lettings, and the enforcement of tenancy
agreements. The successful bidders will also be responsible for managing
vacant properties, caretaking, cleaning, repairs and maintenance.
The government has decided to leave the administration of housing benefit,
operation of the right-to-buy regulations and housing the homeless outside
the tendering package. Councils will continue to be responsible for these
fun-ctions.
Local authorities will be expected to divide their housing stock into
management units of up to 5,000 homes for tendering purposes. However,
authorities with fewer than 7,500 homes can put them out to tender as a
single unit.
Councils will have to consult tenants in drawing up the tender
specification, and will be encouraged to involve them in selecting the
winning bid.
