<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 93 / Warning on cost of water quality
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX, Environment Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WATER BILLS may need to rise by 6 percentage points above annual inflation
for the next five years, Ofwat, the water industry regulator, warned
yesterday.
The rises would be needed to bring water up to new environmental standards,
water companies have told Ofwat.
Mr Ian Byatt, Ofwat's director-general, told a conference yesterday:
'Customers must come first. To tell them that water is good value may be
true, but they do not want to see their disposable income squeezed.'
Mr Byatt has argued frequently over the past year that some standards of
water may be higher than those that are necessary on health grounds, and
that they are pushing up customers' bills.
He called yesterday for ministers to consider the 'trade-off between water
quality and higher bills' when considering how stringently to set new
standards.
Their decisions, he said, would 'set the scene' for Ofwat's wide-ranging
review of the industry's pricing structure next year that will set price
rises for each company for the period 1995 to 2005.
Mr Byatt welcomed recent water company surveys to find out what standards
customers wanted. These confirmed customer anxiety about rising bills. But
several companies found customers willing to pay for the removal of lead
traces from drinking water, even though the cost could reach Pounds 8bn
nationally.
