<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 93 / Japanese manufacturers fuel surge in car output
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UK CAR production jumped by 23.8 per cent last month to reach the highest
total for May in 16 years.
Output rose to 130,374, from 105,234 in the same month a year ago, helped by
the rapid increase in output by Nissan, Toyota and Honda, the three Japanese
carmakers that have located their first European car plants in the UK.
The scale of the increase stems in part from the weak level of output in May
last year, but UK car production has risen strongly in the first five months
of this year with an increase of 9.1 per cent to 608,169.
The jump in output, which is both for export markets and for the domestic
market, is in stark contrast to the steep decline in car output in
continental Europe.
German car production fell by 23.5 per cent in the first four months of the
year to 1.34m, while output in France in the same period fell year-on-year
by 13.6 per cent to 1.06m. In the first quarter output in Spain was 29.9 per
cent lower than in the same period a year ago, and production in Italy fell
by 19.5 per cent.
Output in the UK for export markets in the first five months rose by 8.5 per
cent to 247,438, while output for the domestic market increased by 9.5 per
cent to 360,731, according to figures released by the Society of Motor
Manufacturers and Traders and the Central Statistical Office.
The UK - with Ireland - is the only new-car market in western Europe where
sales are growing, with an increase of 8.9 per cent in the first five
months. Overall new-car sales in western Europe fell year-on-year by about
17.3 per cent.
UK output has been boosted by the start-up of plants by Honda and Toyota
since late last year. In the first three months of this year Japanese car
manufacturers accounted for more than a fifth of UK car production.
The optimism generated by the car sector's performance has been tempered by
the continuing fall in commercial vehicle production, which fell
year-on-year by 32.5 per cent in May and by 20.2 per cent in the first five
months to 89,032.
</TEXT>
