<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 93 / Diners 'liable for tax on tips'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EVEN DINERS who tip waiters will in theory be required to withhold the tax
and pay it to the Inland Revenue, under a controversial judgment from the
Lords yesterday, Andrew Jack writes.
Anyone who tips, or provides payments when there is no contractual
relationship, will become an unofficial tax collector, according to
accountants' interpretations of the law lords' ruling.
The case - Inland Revenue Commissioners vs Herd - concerned a man who had
sold shares in his employers' company back to the company. The Revenue
argued the employer should have deducted tax before making a payment to him.
But the ruling - which found against Mr Herd - suggests a very wide-ranging
definition of what constitutes an employer required to comply with the pay
as you earn tax system. It implies that anyone who pays emoluments to
another person is an employer where the transaction results in pure profit.
Those most directly affected will include employers paying termination money
or those offering introductory payments to new employees.
Ms Leslie Ferrar, a partner at accountants KPMG Peat Marwick, called the
judgment 'a commercial nonsense'. She said it demonstrated the need for a
fundamental overhaul of existing PAYE regulations - only a few weeks after
the Revenue issued a consolidated version of the existing rules.
The Revenue said last night: 'We would need to consider the implications of
the judgment.'
</TEXT>
