<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 93 / Debt-ridden Norco faces liquidation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NORTHERN Co-operative Society, north-east Scotland's biggest retailer,
applied yesterday to go into liquidation, putting 800 full-time and
part-time jobs under threat.
Norco, one of the area's biggest employers for 130 years, said last month it
was trying to save its debt-ridden business through a merger with the
Co-operative Wholesale Society, the main supplier to the whole co-operative
movement and the largest co-operative retail-er.
But a CWS board meeting on Wednesday decided not to proceed with the merger.
Norco said it had not been able to secure adequate support from its bankers
and had no choice but to go into liquida-tion.
Norco said the CWS decision was of 'immense regret' after the 'substantial
progress' Norco had made in reducing its debts in recent months.
CWS said it had considered the merger 'seriously and sympathetically' but
concluded that Norco's problems were mainly of a financial and property
nature rather than concerned with trading, and it was 'extremely late in the
day' for CWS to intervene.
Norco's 89,000 members, who have shares and savings accounts with the
society, and other investors and bondholders are partly protected by the
Co-operative Deposit Protection Scheme. The CWS pledged to provide
additional funds to ensure all investors received full repayment of their
capital. The total involved is believed to be more than Pounds 2m.
A liquidator is expected to be appointed today to investigate whether any
part of Norco can be saved. The society has a superstore in Dundee and 20
convenience stores in north-east Scotland. It employs 200 full-time and 600
part-time staff.
Norco has suffered a dramatic turnaround in its fortunes in three years. In
1990 it was Scotland's biggest co-operative society and its board approved a
Pounds 30m development plan aimed at doubling sales to Pounds 130m in 18
months.
Bank loans took gearing to 200 per cent, which proved impossible to manage
as the recession set in, and the society made a record Pounds 7.4m deficit
in the year to April 1992.
Under pressure from its bankers Norco was forced to sell assets to pay off
its debts. Newly built superstores at Westhill, on the outskirts of
Aberdeen, and at Banchory, Ellon and Elgin were sold to Argyll, owner of
Safeway, the grocery chain.
In March Norco's flagship Berryden store in Aberdeen was sold to Scottish
Co-op, the Scottish retail group of the CWS, for about Pounds 15m, and
Norco's dairy operations were sold to Kennerty Farm Dairies.
</TEXT>
