<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 93 / Slow wage growth raises job hopes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MAY'S SURPRISE fall in unemployment - the fourth in a row - suggests that
the UK labour market has stabilised while subdued wage and cost pressures
yesterday raised hopes that jobless numbers may fall further.
But while Mr David Hunt, the employment secretary, hailed the figures as
'good news' and a 'remarkable achievement', the Department for Employment's
statisticians were in no hurry to declare that unemployment is now firmly on
the downward path.
'They don't want to have a stab at a trend,' the department said. 'We are a
bit cautious. There could still be monthly increases.'
Economists and officials are still unsure why seasonally adjusted
unemployment has declined from its January peak of 2.99m to the provisional
total of 2.91m on May 13.
Unemployment has traditionally been regarded as a lagging indicator of
economic activity. Yet its downward trend in recent months has coincided
with rising industrial production and retail sales.
The latest decline suggests that labour markets have become more responsive
to economic conditions, due in part to trade union reforms and heightened
international competition. If so, Britain is more of a hire and fire
society.
Some support for this can be found in yesterday's employment statistics.
They show that the largest number of hours lost through short-time working
in manufacturing industry in the recent recession was 1.08m in December last
year. During the previous recession, 8m hours were lost in one month in
1980, indicating that companies hoarded labour more at that time.
The figures also go some way to refuting claims that people have been
removed wholesale from the unemployment register through such means as
registering for invalidity benefit. While the UK workforce in employment
fell by 17,000 in the first quarter to 24.92m in March, the number of
employees actually rose to 21.37m from 21.35m in December. The overall drop
reflected falls in the number of self-employed, the armed forces and those
on work-related government training programmes.
Also encouraging was a seasonally-adjusted rise in Jobcentre vacancies
between April and May. Up only 100 to 123,600, the total was the highest for
more than two years.
The unemployment figures also fell in all regions last month except for the
north, where the total stayed the same. Blackspots remain, however. Greater
London's unemployed total fell only 1,600 with the jobless rate staying
unchanged at a higher than average 11.6 per cent. Unemployment in the two
worst areas - Northern Ireland and the north of England - was 13.9 and 12.1
per cent respectively against a national average of 10.4 per cent.
Figures for average earnings, productivity and unit labour costs point to
improved UK competitiveness that may result in a further pick up in the
labour market.
Average earnings rose at an underlying rate of 4 per cent in the year to
April, unchanged from March and the lowest rate of increase for 25 years.
While average earnings in manufacturing rose by an underlying 5 per cent in
April - unchanged from March's figure which was revised up by 0.25 per cent
 -earnings growth in the service sector slowed to 3.5 per cent in April from
3.75 per cent in March.
Manufacturing output per head rose by 2.5 per cent in the three months to
April compared with the previous three months and was 7.8 per cent higher
than in the three months ended April last year.
As a result unit labour costs in manufacturing fell 2.8 per cent in the
three months to April compared with the same 1992 period - the second
biggest fall since statistics were first gathered in 1970.
