<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 93 / ITV takeover stance criticised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SIGNIFICANT shareholder in an ITV company yesterday wrote to Mr Peter
Brooke, national heritage secretary, protesting about the attitude of ITV
management to takeovers.
Mr Nicholas Berry, chairman of Stancroft Trust, which owns 10 per cent of
Grampian, the holder of the ITV franchise for northern Scotland, said ITV
chairmen and chief executives should not be campaigning against a relaxation
of the takeover rules. He said he favoured more ITV takeovers as a way of
realising shareholder value.
In his letter to Mr Brooke Mr Berry said he did not believe that Grampian's
neighbours should be prohibited from taking over the company, since this
would obviously be beneficial to shareholders.
'I believe that similar views would be expressed by shareholders in the
other companies,' said Mr Berry. He added that spokesmen for the companies
involved, often owning a minute number of shares, represented no one but
themselves.
Mr Berry raised the issue following the meeting on Monday between the ITV
chairmen and Mr Brooke to discuss whether there should be a relaxation of
the rules preventing the nine largest ITV companies taking each other over.
There was a majority at the meeting in favour of takeovers among the nine
if, as seems likely, the government does not intend to extend the
'moratorium' on takeovers due to run out at the end of this year.
It is already possible for any European Community company - apart from the
nine ITV groups - to take over an ITV company.
Until the end of the year the Independent Television Commission has to be
informed of a takeover move in advance and has the discretion to block it if
it is judged to be prejudicial to the ITV network. But there is not an
automatic block or moratorium.
A friendly bid from continental Europe or any British company outside the
ranks of the ITV nine would stand a better chance of success than a hostile
one. But the ITC concedes that it could be difficult to decide whether a bid
against an ITV company really was hostile if its shareholders were attracted
by the financial deal.
From January next year the ITC will merely have to check that a bid is
consistent with the rules set by parliament.
</TEXT>
