<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 93 / DTI will talk only to large lobby groups, Heseltine says
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ACCESS TO government ministers is likely to be curtailed for a large number
of trade associations as a result of a policy to restrict contact to a
smaller number of 'lead associations.'
The policy, disclosed in a speech to the Confederation of British Industry
by Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and industry secretary, would apply only
to the industry department - the main channel of government contact for most
trade associations.
The aim is to improve the poor quality of industrial lobbying and reduce the
plethora of sometimes conflicting voices demanding the attention of
ministers.
Smaller trade associations may be required to group together in loose
federations or merge with larger, more powerful organisations, or risk
losing membership.
Mr Heseltine said: 'Too many trade associations are narrowly focused, poorly
resourced and ill-equipped to help the industries they represent.
'In future, where a lead association had emerged in a sector and the subject
of the proposals is relevant to the whole sector, or wider, my officials
would refer to me only proposals from that lead associa-tion.
'Where these representations were received from elsewhere - even from other
trade associations in the sector - my officials would refer them back to the
lead association for co-ordination.' Mr Heseltine said this might create
difficulties but 'there might be no better way to build a single powerful
effective unit to represent the sector'.
He singled out the Chemical Industries Association as the kind of powerfully
resourced association ministers might prefer to deal with. Engineering
companies by comparison were represented by almost 50 associations and 'one
sometimes wonders why'.
Mr Heseltine said: 'There is a general assumption that trade associations in
Britain are weaker and less influential than their counterparts in the US
and many industrial sectors in Europe.'
In future, ministers and officials would be more frank in criticising the
quality of associations to the industrialists that paid for their services.
Mr Heseltine was particularly critical of the way many trade associations
had failed to 'have thought through the implications of the growing European
dimension' of business.
Mr Heseltine announced a new competition under which trade associations
could receive a total of Pounds 500,000. Awards will be made for the '10 or
so' best proposals for establishing 'benchmark' clubs, under which companies
pool information on the best ways of improving competitiveness in areas such
as purchasing or materials handling.
</TEXT>
