<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 93 / Scottish auditors press for change
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE INSTITUTE of Chartered Accountants of Scotland is to launch a lobbying
campaign to support its controversial proposals for the restructuring of
auditing in the UK.
In a document issued this week it suggests the creation of an audit review
panel for every quoted company, independent of management, which would
supervise the appointment of auditors, agree their remuneration and receive
their reports.
It also calls for a substantial increase in the importance of the internal
audit function in companies with the introduction of a chief internal
auditor to be appointed by a committee of non-executive directors.
The institute has submitted its conclusions to bodies including the
Department of Trade and Industry and the Auditing Practices Board. It will
be considering a series of research projects to explore issues in the report
in more detail.
Its document - Auditing into the Twenty-First Century - stresses that
directors should provide greater assurances to the public on whether their
company has adequate resources to continue operating in the future and on
action taken to minimise the risk of fraud.
It says auditors - renamed 'assessors' - should report on the reliability of
internal controls with a detailed statement signed by a named partner in an
accountancy firm.
It says the audit review panel should comprise about three members drawn
from a list held by the Stock Exchange. Members of the panel would appoint
their own successors from the list.
The institute has a reputation for making controversial and influential
recommendations. Several years ago it produced Making Corporate Reports
Valuable, which has formed the basis for many of the recommendations by the
Accounting Standards Board.
Its officials were also instrumental in establishing the Cadbury committee
on the financial aspects of corporate governance, which reported in
December.
Mr Mike Townsend, finance director of Rolls-Royce, said he believed
strengthening internal audit was inevitable, but called the suggestions to
remove power over the auditors from executive directors 'very odd'.
</TEXT>
