<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 93 / 82% of 16-year-olds 'stay in education or training'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS and LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CAREERS services yesterday revealed that 82 per cent of 16-year-olds in the
UK are remaining in full-time education or training.
A study by the National Heads of the Careers Service showed that in England
and Wales alone, 65 per cent of 16-year-olds stayed in full-time education
last year, 13.2 per cent chose youth training and 7.7 per cent employment.
In England and Wales in 1989 18.2 per cent of 16-year-olds went into
employment, while only 48.2 per cent stayed at school. Much of the increase
has been caused by job scarcity. The take-up of youth training has also
fallen, from 21.7 per cent in 1989.
In Northern Ireland 66 per cent stayed in education and 4 per cent entered
employment.
A survey of 224 employers, published yesterday by Industrial Relations
Services, the research organisation, shows that job scarcity will worsen
this year. It found that only a third of employers would definitely recruit
school leavers this summer, with a further quarter uncertain of their plans.
Nearly 40 per cent said they would not recruit school leavers - compared
with 11 per cent last year.
School Leavers' Destinations 1992. ACC Publications, Eaton House, 66a Eaton
Square, London SW1 9BH. Pounds 10.
Employee Development Bulletin 42. IRS, 18-29 Highbury Place, London N5 1QP.
Pounds 20.
</TEXT>
