<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 93 / Bristol and Avon gain new lobby
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM, Wales and West correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A PARTNERSHIP between the public and private sectors in Bristol and Avon has
been set up to agree an economic strategy for the region and to promote it
in the European Community.
The partnership, to be run as a company called the Western Development
Partnership in Avon, has initial funding for the first year of Pounds
250,000 from councils, industry and the Avon Training and Enterprise
Council.
Its formation follows long negotiations amid fears that the effects of the
recession have been exacerbated in Avon and the south-west of England by the
lack of a united voice to represent the region and promote inward
investment. The partnership may eventually include neighbouring counties.
The partnership is supported by councils including Avon, Bristol and Bath,
and by companies, trade unions, professional bodies, universities and
chambers of commerce.
The chairman is Mr David Johnson, a Labour Avon county councillor, and the
vice-chairman is Mr Tony FitzSimons, chief executive of Bristol &amp; West
Building Society.
They said in a joint statement: 'Around 20,000 jobs have been lost in Avon
during the recession and a third of those won't come back even when recovery
gets under way. Avon faces stiff competition from other parts of the UK and
Europe, so we need to act swiftly and decisively to attract inward
investment. At the same time, we want to help existing local businesses to
succeed.'
Other board members include Mr Chris Geoghegan, managing director of British
Aerospace's Airbus division, Mr David Hider, regional chairman of British
Gas South West, and Mr Alfred Morris, vice-chancellor of the University of
the West of England.
Mr Chris Garcia, a strategic planning consultant, has been appointed to
devise a business plan, and a chief executive will be appointed in the
autumn.
Last week the Local Government Commission recommended that the county of
Avon be abolished. Mr FitzSimons said that, in spite of the question over
the county's future, the partnership had agreed to set up a framework to
develop Avon as an important European area.
</TEXT>
