<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 93 / Aid for exporters to be increased
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID DODWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AID FOR exporters under Britain's Aid and Trade Provision is to be increased
this year, targeted mainly at China and Indonesia, the government said
yesterday after a year-long review of the future of ATP, David Dodwell
writes.
The ATP budget for 1993-94 will rise by more than 6 per cent from Pounds
110m to Pounds 117m, mainly as a result of unspent funds available for last
year being carried forward.
The decision to target China and Indonesia follows criticism that the impact
of the ATP budget had been blunted in the past because it had been spread
too thinly across projects in the developing world.
An official said yesterday: 'These are major growth markets where the best
opportunities arise for British companies to win subsequent business on
non-aided terms.'
Other eligible countries - that is creditworthy countries with annual income
per head of less than Dollars 700 (Pounds 466.60) - are India, Ghana,
Lesotho, Pakistan, the Philippines, Sri Lanka and Zimbabwe.
