<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 93 / Station in space gets backing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN and LISA BRANTSEN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Bill Clinton yesterday asked Congress to authorise continued
funding for the space station and the supercollider, the two most expensive
and politically controversial projects on the US high technology agenda.
Mr Clinton selected an amalgam of two preferred options put forward by the
National Aeronautics and Space Administration for the space station,
intended to conduct research into zero-gravity conditions.
The recommended version, endorsing plans for a modular station already on
the drawing board and entailing expenditure of Dollars 10.5bn over the next
five years, would save Dollars 8bn-Dollars 9bn by the planned launch date of
2000-2001.
Mr Clinton is calling for greater financial contributions from other nations
expected to share in the station's research. Some feared it might be
abandoned altogether.
The supercollider (a giant particle accelerator on a 50-mile track) is under
construction at a cost of around Dollars 10bn. Mr Clinton said yesterday to
abandon it 'would signal the US is compromising its position of leadership
in basic science - a position unquestioned for generations'.
</TEXT>
