</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 93 / Diet Pepsi cleared by FDA
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ALLEGATIONS of nationwide tampering with Diet Pepsi cans are unfounded, the
US Food and Drug Administration said yesterday following an investigation.
'We've been unable to confirm even one case of tampering among the dozens of
reports we have received,' Dr David Kessler, FDA commissioner, said in
Washington.
His remarks followed days of confusion, during which dozens of people said
they had found objects - mainly hypodermic needles and syringes - in cans of
Diet Pepsi. The claims first surfaced in the Seattle-Tacoma area of
Washington state, but quickly spread to New Orleans, and then to other
regions.
The FDA said its investigation into the numerous consumer complaints
indicated that the suspect cans had come from disparate Diet Pepsi bottling
plants, with production dates months apart.
'It is simply not logical to conclude that a nationwide tampering has
occurred,' said Dr Kessler. He added that 'a number of people' who had made
complaints were now withdrawing them.
PepsiCo shares closed Dollars 1 1/4 higher, at Dollars 37 7/8 yesterday.
</TEXT>
