<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 93 / Hurd says UN's hands are tied
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Douglas Hurd, the British foreign secretary, said yesterday that United
Nations peacekeeping abilities were hampered by governments failing to
supply enough troops, or not paying their share of the costs on time, Reuter
reports from London.
Mr Hurd, in a speech at a diplomatic banquet in Britain, said the shifting
post-Cold War world had put a heavy burden on the United Nations and
generated increasing calls for it to play a more decisive part in quelling
conflicts.
'It is no use countries arguing for the UN to take an active,
interventionist role and then not putting forward the skilled manpower and
hardware to implement it,' he said.
The UN itself should strengthen its command structure by creating a general
staff of ''highly professional military and civilian experts' to deal with
crises, he said.
'Britain pays her bills on time. So do most of our EC partners, the Nordics
and the countries with a long tradition of peacekeeping such as Australia
and Canada. But some others, who share the heavy burden of international
responsibility, do not,' he said. For operations in Somalia, the former
Yugoslavia and Cambodia, the US owed Dollars 234m, (Pounds 156m), the
Russian Federation Dollars 166m and Germany Dollars 57m, he said.
Mr Boutros Boutros Ghali, the UN secretary general, has called for an extra
7,500 troops to add to the 23,000 already deployed in Bosnia.
</TEXT>
