<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 93 / Stock Exchange criticised over role in Astra collapse
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY and DAVID HELLIER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE STOCK EXCHANGE and accountants Stoy Hayward were roundly criticised
yesterday for their role in events that led to the collapse of Astra
Holdings, the munitions company linked to the Iraqi supergun affair.
A report from the Department of Trade and Industry also showed that Astra's
short, but spectacular, publicly quoted existence began in 1986 in
controversial circumstances.
According to the report, directors of the then private Astra falsified
invoices to boost profits and meet a forecast that allowed it to make a
reverse takeover and become a public company.
Last September the DTI sent the Serious Fraud Office a dossier on the Astra
affair, but the SFO has said it 'did not justify' a criminal investigation.
Former directors of Astra, who were also criticised, tipped off the UK
intelligence services in September 1989 about a suspicious contract under
which their new Belgian subsidiary was supplying propellant to Iraq via
Jordan.
The 560-page report concentrates on the financial circumstances surrounding
the disastrous 1989 acquisition of PRB, a Belgian munitions company, and an
accompanying Pounds 36m rights issue.
It shows serious failures by the Stock Exchange and Paine Webber, Astra's
financial advisers, to ensure proper monitoring of circulars to shareholders
that accompanied the rights issue.
The Exchange allowed the circular to be issued without the normal letter
from Astra's advisers to verify that Astra had adequate working capital.
The Exchange said yesterday it regretted that that had happened. Management
in the new listings department had been changed 15 months ago.
Stoy Hayward, Astra's auditors, were also criticised for not being more
forthcoming with information about the company's parlous working capital
position in 1989 and for signing annual accounts in 1987 that did not
reflect a true and fair view.
Stoy Hayward denied the accusations.
Report details, Page 20
</TEXT>
