<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 93 / Money Markets: Expectations of cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DEALERS IN German money markets remained confident that the Bundesbank would
lower its short term interest rates soon, even though its repo rate remained
unchanged yesterday, writes James Blitz.
In recent days, Bundesbank officials have led the market to think that
monetary policy could be eased because of expectations that M3 money supply
growth would come down.
Expectations of rate-cutting were dampened yesterday after the Bundesbank
announced that the cost of lending short term funds to commercial banks via
the repo rate would remain unchanged at 7.60 per cent.
Short dated Euromark futures reflected some disappointment with the
unchanged policy, the September Euromark contract closing at 93.27, down 3
basis points on the day.
Nevertheless, at this level the contract is still pricing nearly 100 basis
points off three-month German cash in the next 12 weeks, projecting 6.73 per
cent in September.
That view reflects optimism that the Bundesbank will lower its official
rates again, with an outside chance that the discount rate will be reduced
at today's council meeting.
The Bundesbank has been concerned that cuts in German interest rates will
lead to a depreciation of the D-Mark against the dollar and other
currencies, leading to inflation. But it is striking that the D-Mark has
continued to decline in recent weeks in spite of unchanged German policy,
leading to suggestions that it is the scale of the German recession that now
concerns the foreign exchange markets.
At the same time, European central banks take the view that they can cut
rates to below German levels whatever the Bundesbank does. The Danes,
Italians and French have all cut rates in the past week.
Sterling markets were slightly more bullish for lower UK base rates
following Mr Kenneth Clarke's speech on Tuesday night.
The emphasis of the speech was on fostering UK growth and this helped the
September short sterling contract to rise 2 basis points on the day to
94.19.
Three-month sterling cash was  1/16 percentage point softer at 5 7/8 per
cent, helped by the swift despatch of a small daily shortage of Pounds 550m
in the discount market.
</TEXT>
