<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 93 / International Company News: US 'warehouse clubs' in deal to
merge operations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A MERGER was announced yesterday between two of the largest operators of
'warehouse clubs' in the US.
San Diego-based Price Company, which pioneered the highly-successful retail
concept, and Costco, with headquarters at Kirkland, near Seattle, announced
yesterday that they planned to combine their operations in a new company
called Price/Costco.
It will take in 195 membership warehouses - huge out-of-town retail barns,
which sell merchandise at rock-bottom prices - in three countries. Annual
sales will stand at around Dollars 16bn. Both have disclosed plans to open
warehouse club outlets in the UK - with Price Club setting up a joint
venture with Littlewoods.
Under the deal, shares in the new company will be issued on the basis of
2.13 shares for each Price Company share, and one share for each Costco
share. Price Company shareholders will own about 48 per cent of the new
merged group, while Costco shareholders, who include France's Carrefour,
will have 52 per cent. Price shares soared Dollars 5 3/4 to Dollars 38 on
the news, while Costco gained Dollars 1 3/4 to close at Dollars 18 3/4 .
Top positions at the merged company will be filled by executives from both
companies, and the Price/Costco board will comprise an equal number of
directors. There will be home offices in both San Diego and Kirkland,
although the information and accounting systems will be centred in the
former city, and buying and merchandising in the latter.
The warehouse club movement has been one of the most dynamic elements in the
US retail sector in the recent years, where sales reached around Dollars
33bn in 1992. However, sales have slowed sharply recently, and analysts have
noted that certain geographical markets were over-crowded.
Accordingly, there have been predictions of consolidations. Last month,
Wal-Mart Stores, the largest US operator of warehouse clubs through its Sams
Club chain, said it was buying 14 outlets from Kmart, the number two
operator via the Pace Membership Warehouses. Costco and Price Company rank
third and fourth respectively, in terms of outlets operated.
</TEXT>
