<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 93 / International Company News: Daimler sees significant profits
recovery next year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STUTTGART
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DAIMLER-BENZ, Germany's largest industrial company, is on course for a
significant profits recovery next year, the group's finance director said
yesterday.
Mr Gerhard Liener said that next year's profits could be twice as high as in
the current year. This means a figure of around DM2bn (Dollars 1.25bn) for
next year after an expected DM1bn for this year and DM1.45bn last year.
The prediction will surprise analysts who have been whittling back their
forecasts in the wake of the group's dire first-quarter figures.
Last month, Daimler announced that it made net profits of just DM20m for the
first quarter of the year, down from DM480m in the same period last year.
Mr Liener's optimism is based primarily on high expectations for the group's
Mercedes-Benz luxury car subsidiary which this week launched its new C-class
smaller executive car, the long-awaited successor to the 11-year-old
Mercedes-Benz 190-Series.
Combined with the impact of cost-cutting measures across the Daimler-Benz
group as a whole, the effect will be a 'fundamental improvement' in
Daimler's profitability from 1994 onwards.
The profits will feed through early enough to ensure that the group makes
about DM1bn net profit for the whole of this year, he said.
'The C-class is a great success story,' Mr Liener. 'It was only this week
that the model was presented to the German public and I can already predict
that every C-class car we produce this year will be sold without having to
grant any discount.'
The production target for the new model for this year is 120,000 units, Mr
Liener said, rising to 240,000 next year. He said that 40,000 units have
been ordered in Germany. For next year, he said order volume could be in the
region of 260,000 to 270,000, which compares to annual sales of 190,000 of
the 190-Series over the past decade.
Mr Liener said that by the middle of 1994, the group would have cut 40,000
jobs, approximately 10 per cent of the workforce, since the beginning of the
economic downturn in Germany.
The total cost of these measures will be DM3bn-DM4bn which will be booked
against current year profits; the annual savings in 1994 onwards will be in
the same order of magnitude.
'By next year all the costs associated with the reduction of the workforce
will have been digested,' Mr Liener said, 'that is why I feel so confident
that 1994 profits will be considerably increased on the 1993 figures. They
could be as much as double the current year figures.'
He predicted that the severity of the recession in Germany this year would
have abated somewhat by next year, partly as a result of lower interest
rates.
This would help the group's performance, as would an expected strengthening
of the US dollar versus the D-Mark which could provide an impetus to the
group's export sales later this year.
Scepticism about the group's profit outlook has caused the Daimler share
price to fall this year to DM602.40 down from a high this year of DM628.50.
Present expectations for next year's net profits range from DM1.1bn to
DM1.4bn.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Daimler-Benz.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>DEZ  Germany, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
