<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 93 / International Company News: Ferruzzi creditors meet Bank of
Italy officials
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
LEADING bank creditors of Italy's troubled Ferruzzi group met Bank of Italy
officials yesterday as the collapse in the company's share price took on a
new political dimension.
The meeting came against signs that foreign banks, which have lent to
Ferruzzi, might be invited on to the five-bank committee of leading
creditors. Mr Guido Rosa, the local head of France's Societe Generale and
chairman of the foreign bankers' association in Italy, may join the talks as
the foreigners' representative.
The Bank of Italy has moved into the fray as the scale of Ferruzzi's
financial difficulties have become more evident in recent days. The group
and family holding company is known to have total borrowings of about
L31,000bn (Dollars 20.9bn).
Brokers are asking why warning bells at the Bank of Italy, which is supposed
to supervise the scale of bank lending to individual companies, did not
sound earlier.
Separately, Mr Vincenzo Visco, deputy chairman of the finance committee of
the upper house of parliament, strongly criticised the rescue operation
being mounted by Mediobanca and the other leading bank creditors.
Mr Visco, briefly finance minister in the new Ciampi government, drew
attention to the use of public sector banks to rescue a private company.
'I don't believe taxpayers' money . . . can be used by Mr Cuccia with the
ease to which he has accustomed us in the past'. Mr Enrico Cuccia is
Mediobanca's honorary chairman.
Other critics of the lifeline, which remains shrouded in mystery, have
pointed to the possibility of public sector banks swapping loans to Ferruzzi
for equity - potentially nationalising the company at a time when Italy is
supposed to be privatising its state-controlled banking sector.
The attacks came against a further day of sharp falls for shares in Ferruzzi
Finanziaria (Ferfin) the main holding company, and its subsidiaries. Ferfin
stock plunged a further 16.6 per cent to L494.8 from L593.5, while shares in
Montedison, the main industrial subsidiary, dropped to L750, making for a
cumulative drop of over 23 per cent since Friday's close.
Investors showed their hostility to this week's surprise rights issue by
Fondiaria, the Ferruzzi-controlled insurance group, by marking its shares
down by almost 8 per cent to L22,201 from L24,101.
Fondiaria stock has now tumbled over 17 per cent since the deal was
announced late on Monday.
The precipitous falls and the fact that many of Ferruzzi's operations are
backed by attractive industrial assets has not yet triggered any bargain
hunting, although prices recovered somewhat in after-hours' trading. The
explanation lies partly in the widespread cynicism towards Mediobanca, which
has a reputation for ignoring minority investors, and the continued silence
about the rescue plans.
Mr Enzo Berlanda, chairman of the Consob companies and stock exchange
watchdog, yesterday said brokers' reactions have been 'excessive and
premature' in view of the fact that details of the rescue were not yet
available.
However, the legacy of hostility in the bourse towards Mediobanca and
opacity of the Ferruzzi rescue project means investors are still willing to
ditch shares at almost any price. That sentiment has hit stock in the five
most exposed creditor banks and the market in general, which has fallen for
four days running.
</TEXT>
