<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 93 / UK Company News: Kembrey
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Kembrey, a maker of electrical connectors and accessories, returned to
profit in the second half of 1992-93, overcoming the first half loss, and Mr
David Burnet, chairman, said he expected a further recovery in the current
year.
Pre-tax profit for the 53 weeks to April 3 emerged at Pounds 11,000 - better
than the directors expected at halfway when a loss of Pounds 114,000 was
reported. The previous year's deficit was Pounds 347,000.
Mr Burnet said that no clear trend had emerged for the current year, but he
hoped that profits would improve and borrowings decline further. He said
that the weight of any improvement would probably be heavily biased towards
the second half.
Turnover was lower at Pounds 22m (Pounds 27.4m). Extraordinary costs in the
year fell from Pounds 741,000 to Pounds 441,000 and related to losses on the
disposal of non-core businesses Despro and Dalforsan. Redundancies
throughout the group cost Pounds 189,000.
Net borrowings have come down by Pounds 1.27m to Pounds 4.3m. After the
extraordinary items and the cost of the proposed dividend of 0.155p (0.15p),
there was a deficiency on the profits and loss account of Pounds 472,000
(Pounds 1.14m) which was met from reserves.
Earnings per share were 0.04p (1.24p losses).
